  "title": "Foundation Models Enabling Multi-Scale Battery Materials Discovery: From Molecules To Devices",
  "experiments_summary": "The study evaluates chemical foundation models (FMs) pre-trained on SMILES representations for predicting battery material properties across multiple scales. Ten prediction tasks were examined: molecular properties (oxidation/reduction potentials, HOMO/LUMO levels from D3TaLES database), formulation manufacturability (solubility of 3,300 salt-solvent combinations measured experimentally), formulation performance (ionic conductivity from 18,000 literature datapoints), surface contact characteristics (contact angle measurements of 119 electrolyte formulations on four separators using sessile drop technique), and device performance (Coulombic Efficiency from 150 datapoints, LiI battery capacity from 125 datapoints, Li-ICl battery capacity from 91 datapoints). Four FMs were compared: SMI-TED (pre-trained on 91M molecules), MolT5 (100M SMILES + text descriptions), Galactica (2M SMILES + scientific literature), and GraphMVP (graph-based with 3D conformers), benchmarked against Morgan Fingerprints. Transfer learning was used to generate molecular embeddings, which were aggregated by composition-weighted addition for formulations and concatenated with device variables (temperature, separator labels, cathode loading). Neural networks with 2-3 hidden layers (500-250-100 or 500-250 nodes, ReLU activation) were trained using 80-20 train-test splits with 5-fold cross-validation. Out-of-distribution performance was assessed using tail-end outcome distributions and chemical similarity metrics (cosine similarity of embeddings). Interpretability was evaluated by correlating 550+ chemical moieties (identified via SMARTS matching) with outcomes using Spearman's correlation coefficient, comparing actual vs. predicted correlations in train and test sets."
